   "source": [
    "<h3> a) Import the series of a given frequency as a data frame in R. </h3>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "b6eb7be4",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2023-11-20T11:02:20.117670Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2023-11-20T11:02:20.085727Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2023-11-20T11:02:20.677585Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2023-11-20T11:02:20.675722Z"
    },
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.610244,
     "end_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:20.680162",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:20.069918",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "DataMonthly <- read_xlsx(path = \"/kaggle/input/casestudydataset/PredictorData2022.xlsx\", sheet = \"Monthly\")\n",
    "DataQuarterly <- read_xlsx(path = \"/kaggle/input/casestudydataset/PredictorData2022.xlsx\", sheet =\"Quarterly\" )\n",
    "DataAnnual <- read_xlsx(path = \"/kaggle/input/casestudydataset/PredictorData2022.xlsx\", sheet = \"Annual\")\n",
    "\n",
    "new_colnames_dict <- c(\n",
    "  \"Time\" = \"yyyymm\",\n",
    "  \"Time\" = \"yyyyq\",\n",
    "  \"Time\" = \"yyyy\",\n",
    "  \"SP500_Index\" = \"Index\",\n",
    "  \"Dividends_12MonthSum\" = \"D12\",\n",
    "  \"Earnings_12MonthSum\" = \"E12\",\n",
    "  \"BookToMarket_Ratio\" = \"b/m\",\n",
    "  \"TreasuryBill_Rate\" = \"tbl\",\n",
    "  \"AAA_CorporateBond_Yield\" = \"AAA\",\n",
    "  \"BAA_CorporateBond_Yield\" = \"BAA\",\n",
    "  \"LongTermGovBond_Yield\" = \"lty\",\n",
    "  \"NetEquityExpansion\" = \"ntis\",\n",
    "  \"RiskFree_Rate\" = \"Rfree\",\n",
    "  \"Inflation_CPI\" = \"infl\",\n",
    "  \"LongTermRateOfReturn\" = \"ltr\",\n",
    "  \"CorporateBond_Return\" = \"corpr\",\n",
    "  \"StockVariance\" = \"svar\",\n",
    "  \"CrossSectionalPremium\" = \"csp\",\n",
    "  \"ConsumptionWealthIncomeRatio\" = \"cay\", #check these variables\n",
    "  \"InvestmentCapitalRatio\" = \"ik\",\n",
    "  \"Dividend3YearPriceRatio\" = \"D3\",\n",
    "  \"Earnings3YearPriceRatio\" = \"E3\",\n",
    "  \"ConsumptionWealthIncomeRatioMonthly\" = \"caym\",\n",
    "  \"PercentageEquityIssuing\" = \"eqis\"\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "filtered_dict_monthly <- new_colnames_dict[new_colnames_dict %in% colnames(DataMonthly)]\n",
    "DataMonthly <- rename(DataMonthly, !!!filtered_dict_monthly)\n",
    "\n",
    "filtered_dict_quarterly <- new_colnames_dict[new_colnames_dict %in% colnames(DataQuarterly)]\n",
    "DataQuarterly <- rename(DataQuarterly, !!!filtered_dict_quarterly)\n",
    "\n",
    "filtered_dict_annual <- new_colnames_dict[new_colnames_dict %in% colnames(DataAnnual)]\n",
    "DataAnnual <- rename(DataAnnual, !!!filtered_dict_annual)\n",
    "\n",
    "for(i in names(DataMonthly)) {\n",
    "  if(class(DataMonthly[[i]]) == \"character\") {\n",
    "    DataMonthly[[i]] <- as.numeric(DataMonthly[[i]])\n",
    "  }\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "for(i in names(DataQuarterly)) {\n",
    "  if(class(DataQuarterly[[i]]) == \"character\") {\n",
    "    DataQuarterly[[i]] <- as.numeric(DataQuarterly[[i]])\n",
    "  }\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "for(i in names(DataAnnual)) {\n",
    "  if(class(DataAnnual[[i]]) == \"character\") {\n",
    "    DataAnnual[[i]] <- as.numeric(DataAnnual[[i]])\n",
    "  }\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "DataMonthly$Time <- zoo::as.yearmon(as.character(DataMonthly$Time), format=\"%Y%m\")\n",
    "DataQuarterly$Time <- zoo::as.yearqtr(as.character(DataQuarterly$Time), format=\"%Y%q\")\n",
    "DataAnnual$Time <- zoo::as.yearmon(paste0(as.character(DataAnnual$Time), \"-01\"), format=\"%Y-%m\")\n",
    "\n",
    "DataMonthly %<>% select(-CRSP_SPvw, -CRSP_SPvwx)\n",
    "DataQuarterly %<>% select(-CRSP_SPvw, -CRSP_SPvwx)\n",
    "DataAnnual %<>% select(-CRSP_SPvw, -CRSP_SPvwx)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#Calculate Returns\n",
    "calculate_returns <- function(input){\n",
    "  input %<>% mutate(returns = as.vector(quantmod::Delt(SP500_Index))) \n",
    "  input %<>% mutate(ExcessReturn = returns - RiskFree_Rate)\n",
    "  input %<>% select(-returns, -RiskFree_Rate, -SP500_Index)\n",
    "  return(input)\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Lag Predictors\n",
    "lag_predictors <- function(input){\n",
    "  output <- input %>%\n",
    "    mutate(across(-c(Time, ExcessReturn), lag, .names = \"lag_{.col}\")) %>% \n",
    "    select(Time, ExcessReturn, starts_with(\"lag_\")) %>% \n",
    "    slice(-1) \n",
    "  return(output)\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Function for fitting Linear Model with all predictors\n",
    "\n",
    "# Data Preprocessing\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "DataMonthly %<>% calculate_returns()\n",
    "DataQuarterly %<>% calculate_returns()\n",
    "DataAnnual %<>% calculate_returns()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "DataMonthly %<>% lag_predictors()\n",
    "DataQuarterly %<>% lag_predictors()\n",
    "DataAnnual %<>% lag_predictors()"
   ]
  },

    "excess_return_plot <- function(data) {\n",
    "  options(repr.plot.width = 14, repr.plot.height = 6)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  ggplot(data, aes(y = ExcessReturn, x = Time)) +\n",
    "    geom_line(color = \"blue\", linewidth = 0.5, linetype = 1) +\n",
    "    theme_ipsum() +\n",
    "    ggtitle(\"Excess Return Time Series\")\n",
    "}\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# ACF & PACF Analysis\n",
    "<h3> c) Further explore the structure of the excess returns series, this time exploring some time series aspects like serial correlation and variance. For that, you will produce plots of the ACF and PACF.</h3>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f83b1452",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.017603,
     "end_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:22.399150",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:22.381547",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "The ACF helps identify seasonality and provides information about how past values of the series are correlated with the present. The PACF, on the other hand, helps identify the order of the AR model and the direct influences between different time lags. Together, they provide insights into the temporal structure of a time series, which is crucial for time series modeling and forecasting."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9022ffc3",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.017563,
     "end_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:22.434443",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:22.416880",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "**Auto-Correlation Function (ACF):**\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Lag vs. Auto-Correlation Value:** The ACF plot is a bar chart where the x-axis represents the number of lags (time intervals) and the y-axis represents the correlation values. Each bar represents the correlation between the original time series and the same series lagged by a certain number of time intervals.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Interpreting ACF Peaks:** If there's a significant peak at a specific lag (say, lag 1 it suggests a strong correlation between the time series at that lag and the previous time step. This indicates a seasonality pattern.\n",
    "If the ACF decays gradually and does not show any distinct peaks, it suggests a non-seasonal time series.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Damped Oscillation:** When you see oscillations that slowly decrease in magnitude as lags increase, this can indicate a time series with a damping effect, which is common in many economic and financial time series."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "58fe8a1f",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.017597,
     "end_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:22.469574",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:22.451977",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "**Partial Auto-Correlation Function (PACF):**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Lag vs. Partial Auto-Correlation Value**: The PACF plot also has lags on the x-axis and correlation values on the y-axis. The PACF at lag k represents the correlation between the original series and the same series lagged by k time intervals, while controlling for the influence of all shorter lags.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Interpreting PACF Peaks**: Significant spikes at specific lags suggest direct relationships or influences between the current time step and the time step at that particular lag.\n",
    "Significant spikes outside of the first few lags indicate partial correlations that aren't explained by shorter lags.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Identifying AR Order**: The PACF plot is particularly useful for identifying the order of an Auto-Regressive (AR) model. You typically look for the last significant spike before the plot drops to zero. This lag corresponds to the order of the AR model.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "**Monthly Data**: \n",
    "* The **ACF** plot reveals a notable positive autocorrelation at lag1 suggesting a positive correlation between Excess Returns and their own lagged values. This implies a tendency for similar Excess Returns to follow in the next period.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Similarly, the **PACF** plot shows a significant positive partial autocorrelation at lag 1 confirming first-order autocorrelation in the Excess Returns series. Additionally, notable partial autocorrelations at lags 13 and 14 suggest potential seasonal autocorrelation, possibly influenced by factors like investor sentiment, economic conditions,and market trends.\n",
    "\n",
    "**In summary, both ACF and PACF plots display a significant decay in autocorrelation coefficients after the first lag, indicating weak stationarity in the Excess Return series.**"
   ]
  },

    "**Quarterly Data**: \n",
    "* The ACF and PACF plots indicate notable seasonal serial correlation at lags 3 and 7 for quarterly Excess Returns. This implies positive correlation between Excess Returns in a quarter and those in the corresponding quarter of  the previous year and two years ago. \n",
    "\n",
    "* Some evidence of serial correlation is also observed at lag 1, although it is weaker compared to lags 3 and 7.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Additionally, the plots highlight a rapid decay in serial correlation after lag 7, suggesting that quarterly Excess Returns behave as white noise beyond this point."

    "Annual Data \n",
    "* The absence of significant ACF or PACF values beyond lag 5 for annual frequency data suggests that the negative serial correlation observed at lags 2 and 5 is not sustained beyond these points. This indicates that the influence of returns from previous years on the current year’s return diminishes after the fifth year, emphasizing a changing pattern in the series over longer time horizons.\n",
    "\n",
    "* The persistent high variance underscores the continued volatility and unpredictability of Excess Returns."
   ]

   "source": [
    "# Model Selection based on Information Criteria"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4524cbc5",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.021843,
     "end_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:23.695984",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:23.674141",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "Information criteria are statistical measures used in model selection and evaluation. They help determine the quality of statistical models by balancing goodness of fit and model complexity. The primary purpose of information criteria is to select the most appropriate model among a set of candidate models, with the goal of choosing a model that effectively describes the data while avoiding overfitting "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dd513064",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.021149,
     "end_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:23.738108",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:23.716959",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "**Akaike Information Criterion (AIC)** \n",
    "* The AIC measures the quality of a model by considering both the goodness of fit and the number of parameters in the model. \n",
    "\n",
    "* A lower AIC value indicates a better model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3430b3f8",
   "metadata": {
    "papermill": {
     "duration": 0.02144,
     "end_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:23.784700",
     "exception": false,
     "start_time": "2023-11-20T11:02:23.763260",
     "status": "completed"
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "**Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)**\n",
    "* The BIC, also known as the Schwarz Information Criterion (SIC), penalizes model complexity more strongly than AIC.\n",
    "* It balances the goodness of fit and model complexity, favoring simpler models."
   ]
  },
  {

    "# Function to fit ARIMA models and calculate information criteria\n",
    "\n",
    "fit_arima_and_info_criteria <- function(x, p) {\n",
    "  arima_model <- arima(x, order = c(p, 0, 0))\n",
    "\n",
    "  loglik <- sum(log(dnorm(x - arima_model$resid)))\n",
    "  n <- length(x)\n",
    "\n",
    "  aic <- AIC(arima_model)\n",
    "  bic <- BIC(arima_model)\n",
    "\n",
    "  info_df <- data.frame(p = p, AIC = aic, BIC = bic)\n",
    "  return(info_df)\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit ARIMA models for different values of p\n",
    "p_max <- 10  # Set the maximum order\n",
    "info_criteria_list <- lapply(1:p_max, function(p) fit_arima_and_info_criteria(DataMonthly$ExcessReturn, p))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Combine the results into a data frame\n",
    "info_criteria_df <- do.call(rbind, info_criteria_list)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the plot\n",
    "plot <- ggplot(info_criteria_df, aes(x = p)) +\n",
    "  geom_line(aes(y = AIC, color = \"AIC\"), linetype = \"solid\", size = 0.5) +\n",
    "  geom_line(aes(y = BIC, color = \"BIC\"), linetype = \"solid\", size = 0.5) +\n",
    "  labs(title = \"Information Criteria for AR(p) Models with Monthly Data\",\n",
    "       y = \"Information Criterion\",\n",
    "       x = \"Order of AR Model (p)\") +\n",
    "  theme_minimal() +\n",
    "  theme(legend.position = \"top\") +\n",
    "  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:p_max) +  # To ensure integer x-axis labels\n",
    "  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"AIC\" = \"red\", \"BIC\" = \"black\")) +\n",
    "  guides(color = guide_legend(title = \"Information Criterion\")) +\n",
    "  theme(\n",
    "    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust X-axis label size and weight\n",
    "    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust Y-axis label size and weight\n",
    "    axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"), # Adjust axis title (x and y) size and weight\n",
    "    legend.text = element_text(size = 12, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust legend text size and weight\n",
    "    legend.title = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\") \n",
    "  )\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display the plot\n",
    "plot\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "p1_max = 10\n",
    "info_criteria_list <- lapply(1:p1_max, function(p) fit_arima_and_info_criteria(DataQuarterly$ExcessReturn, p))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Combine the results into a data frame\n",
    "info_criteria_df <- do.call(rbind, info_criteria_list)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the plot\n",
    "plot <- ggplot(info_criteria_df, aes(x = p)) +\n",
    "  geom_line(aes(y = AIC, color = \"AIC\"), linetype = \"solid\", size = 0.5) +\n",
    "  geom_line(aes(y = BIC, color = \"BIC\"), linetype = \"solid\", size = 0.5) +\n",
    "  labs(title = \"Information Criteria for AR(p) Models with Quarterly Data\",\n",
    "       y = \"Information Criterion\",\n",
    "       x = \"Order of AR Model (p)\") +\n",
    "  theme_minimal() +\n",
    "  theme(legend.position = \"top\") +\n",
    "  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:p1_max) +  # To ensure integer x-axis labels\n",
    "  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"AIC\" = \"red\", \"BIC\" = \"black\")) +\n",
    "  guides(color = guide_legend(title = \"Information Criterion\")) +\n",
    "  theme(\n",
    "    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust X-axis label size and weight\n",
    "    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust Y-axis label size and weight\n",
    "    axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"), # Adjust axis title (x and y) size and weight\n",
    "    legend.text = element_text(size = 12, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust legend text size and weight\n",
    "    legend.title = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\") \n",
    "  )\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display the plot\n",
    "plot"
   ]
  },

    "p2_max = 10\n",
    "info_criteria_list <- lapply(1:p2_max, function(p) fit_arima_and_info_criteria(DataAnnual$ExcessReturn, p))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Combine the results into a data frame\n",
    "info_criteria_df <- do.call(rbind, info_criteria_list)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the plot\n",
    "plot <- ggplot(info_criteria_df, aes(x = p)) +\n",
    "  geom_line(aes(y = AIC, color = \"AIC\"), linetype = \"solid\", size = 0.5) +\n",
    "  geom_line(aes(y = BIC, color = \"BIC\"), linetype = \"solid\", size = 0.5) +\n",
    "  labs(title = \"Information Criteria for AR(p) Models with Annual Data\",\n",
    "       y = \"Information Criterion\",\n",
    "       x = \"Order of AR Model (p)\") +\n",
    "  theme_minimal() +\n",
    "  theme(legend.position = \"top\") +\n",
    "  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:p2_max) +  # To ensure integer x-axis labels\n",
    "  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"AIC\" = \"red\", \"BIC\" = \"black\")) +\n",
    "  guides(color = guide_legend(title = \"Information Criterion\")) +\n",
    "  theme(\n",
    "    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust X-axis label size and weight\n",
    "    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust Y-axis label size and weight\n",
    "    axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\"), # Adjust axis title (x and y) size and weight\n",
    "    legend.text = element_text(size = 12, face = \"bold\"),  # Adjust legend text size and weight\n",
    "    legend.title = element_text(size = 14, face = \"bold\") \n",
    "  )\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display the plot\n",
    "plot"
   ]

    "# Autoregressive Model/ AR(p)\n",
    "The Autoregressive Model (AR(p)) is a fundamental time series modeling technique used to predict a variable based on its previous *p* values. It is expressed as:\n",
    "\n",
    "*X<sub>t</sub>* = *φ<sub>0</sub>* + *φ<sub>1</sub>**X<sub>t-1</sub> +...\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- *X<sub>t</sub>* denotes the value of the time series at time *t*.\n",
    "- *φ<sub>0</sub>* is the intercept term, representing the baseline value of the time series.\n",
    "- *φ<sub>1</sub>, φ<sub>2</sub>, ..., φ<sub>p</sub>* are the parameters of the model, indicating the influence of the previous *p* values on the current value.\n",
    "- *X<sub>t-1</sub>, X<sub>t-2</sub>, ..., X<sub>t-p</sub>* represent the lagged values of the time series, influencing the current value.\n",
    "- *ε<sub>t</sub>* is the white noise error term, capturing the random variability in the observed data.\n",
    "\n",
    "The AR(p) model utilizes the past *p* observations to forecast the current value of the time series. It assumes a linear relationship between the present value and its previous values, incorporating their weighted effects along with a random error term.\n",
    "\n",
    "This model serves as a basis for analyzing and forecasting time series data, aiding in understanding patterns and trends based on historical information.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

    "fmse_ar_monthly <- 0\n",
    "fmse_ar_quarterly <- 0\n",
    "fmse_ar_annual <- 0\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "ar_modelling <- function(input, order) {\n",
    "  \n",
    "    \n",
    "  AR_p <- ar(input$ExcessReturn, aic = FALSE,\n",
    "             order.max = order,\n",
    "             method = c(\"yule-walker\"),\n",
    "             demean = FALSE, series = \"AR(p)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "  # Calculate fitted values\n",
    "  fitted_values <- input$ExcessReturn - AR_p$res\n",
    "\n",
    "  plot_data <- data.frame(\n",
    "    Date = input$Time,\n",
    "    Excess_Returns = input$ExcessReturn,\n",
    "    Fitted = fitted_values\n",
    "  )\n",
    "\n",
    "  AR_FMSE <- mean(AR_p$resid^2, na.rm = TRUE)^0.5\n",
    "\n",
    "  options(repr.plot.width = 14, repr.plot.height = 6)\n",
    "\n",
    "  # Plot data using ggplot2\n",
    "  plot <- ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Date)) +\n",
    "    geom_line(aes(y = Excess_Returns, color = \"Observed\")) +\n",
    "    geom_line(aes(y = Fitted, color = \"Forecasted\")) +\n",
    "    labs(title = \"Excess Returns with AR(2) Fitted Values\") +\n",
    "    theme_minimal() +\n",
    "    scale_color_manual(name = \"Excess Return\", values = c(Observed = \"grey\", Forecasted = \"blue\")) + theme(legend.position = \"top\")\n",
    "  # Display the plot\n",
    "ggsave(\"AR_Annualy.jpeg\", plot, width = 14, height = 6)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  residuals = AR_p$res\n",
    " if (identical(input, DataMonthly)) {\n",
    "  fmse_ar_monthly <<- AR_FMSE\n",
    "\n",
    "} else if (identical(input, DataQuarterly)) {\n",
    "  fmse_ar_quarterly <<- AR_FMSE\n",
    "\n",
    "} else if (identical(input, DataAnnual)) {\n",
    "  fmse_ar_annual <<- AR_FMSE\n",
    "}\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(plot)\n",
    "return( FMSE = paste0(\"FMSE: \", AR_FMSE))\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# MSFE Analysis for AR modelling\n",
    "**The Mean Squared Forecast Error (MSFE)** values in the table represent the average squared difference between the forecasted values and the actual values for each frequency and autoregressive order. \n",
    "\n",
    "Lower MSFE values generally indicate more accurate forecasts. Therefore, in this context, the model performs relatively better in terms of accuracy for Monthly frequency compared to Quarterly and Annual frequencies as longer time intervals between observations can lead to a greater accumulation of uncertainties, making it more challenging to accurately predict annual variations.\n",
    "\n",
    "|                    | **Monthly, $p=1$** | **Quarterly, $p=4$** | **Annual, $p=2$** |\n",
    "|------------------- | ------------------- | --------------------- | ----------------- |\n",
    "| **AR($p$) MSFE**   | 0.047168            | 0.094406              | 0.185140          |\n",
    "\n",
    "                        Table1: Autoregressive Model MSFE for Different Frequencies*\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, stock returns may be influenced by complex economic and market dynamics that are difficult to capture accurately in a predictive model. Factors such as frequent financial reporting cycles, macroeconomic changes, and policy shifts may introduce more variability in stock returns, making it challenging to achieve precise predictions in real-life scenarios.\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Predictive Models\n",
    "\n",
    "Predictive models aim to predict a continuous outcome variable (\\(Y\\)) based on one or more predictor variables (\\(X_1, X_2, ..., X_n\\)). The model is expressed as:\n",
    "\n",
    "Y = β₀ + β₁X₁ + β₂X₂ + ... + βₙXₙ + ε\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- \\(Y\\): Outcome variable\n",
    "- \\(X₁, X₂......Xₙ ): Predictor variables\n",
    "- \\(β₀): Intercept\n",
    "- \\(β₁, β₂, ..., βₙ\\): Coefficients\n",
    "- \\(ε\\): Error term\n",
    "\n",
    "This model provides a straightforward way to express the relationship between predictors and the response in a linear fashion.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Function to calculate RMSE for each predictor alone\n",
    "RMSE_LM <- function(df) {\n",
    "  excluded_columns <- c(\"SP500_Index\", \"Returns\", \"ExcessReturn\", \"Time\")\n",
    "\n",
    "  # Get the names of the columns to use as covariates\n",
    "  covariate_names <- setdiff(names(df), excluded_columns)\n",
    "  # Initialize an empty dataframe to store RMSE values\n",
    "  rmse_df <- data.frame(Predictor = character(0), RMSE = numeric(0))\n",
    "\n",
    "  # Loop through each covariate and fit a linear model\n",
    "  for (covariate in covariate_names) {\n",
    "    formula <- as.formula(paste(\"ExcessReturn ~\", covariate))\n",
    "    model <- lm(formula, data = df)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Calculate RMSE\n",
    "    rmse <- mean(model$residuals^2)^0.5\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Add RMSE to the dataframe\n",
    "    rmse_df <- rbind(rmse_df, data.frame(Predictor = covariate, RMSE = rmse))\n",
    "    \n",
    "  }\n",
    "  rmse_df <- rmse_df[order(rmse_df$RMSE), ]\n",
    "  return()\n",
    "}\n",
    "RMSE_LM(DataMonthly)\n",
    "RMSE_LM(DataQuarterly)\n",
    "RMSE_LM(DataAnnual)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "RMSE_LM_MultipleDatasets <- function(DataMonthly, DataQuarterly, DataAnnual) {\n",
    "  datasets <- list(DataMonthly, DataQuarterly, DataAnnual)\n",
    "  dataset_names <- c(\"DataMonthly\", \"DataQuarterly\", \"DataAnnual\")\n",
    "  excluded_columns <- c(\"SP500_Index\", \"Returns\", \"ExcessReturn\", \"Time\")\n",
    "\n",
    "  # Initialize an empty dataframe to store RMSE values\n",
    "  rmse_df <- data.frame(Dataset = character(0), Predictor = character(0), RMSE = numeric(0))\n",
    "\n",
    "  for (i in 1:length(datasets)) {\n",
    "    df <- datasets[[i]]\n",
    "    dataset_name <- dataset_names[i]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Get the names of the columns to use as covariates\n",
    "    covariate_names <- setdiff(names(df), excluded_columns)\n",
    "\n",
    "    for (covariate in covariate_names) {\n",
    "      formula <- as.formula(paste(\"ExcessReturn ~\", covariate))\n",
    "      model <- lm(formula, data = df)\n",
    "\n",
    "      # Calculate RMSE\n",
    "      rmse <- mean(model$residuals^2)^0.5\n",
    "\n",
    "      # Add RMSE to the dataframe\n",
    "      rmse_df <- bind_rows(rmse_df, data.frame(Dataset = dataset_name, Predictor = covariate, RMSE = rmse))\n",
    "    }\n",
    "  }\n",
    "\n",
    "  rmse_df <- rmse_df[order(rmse_df$Dataset, rmse_df$RMSE), ]\n",
    "  return(rmse_df)\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "result <- RMSE_LM_MultipleDatasets(DataMonthly, DataQuarterly, DataAnnual)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Reshape the result dataframe\n",
    "result_wide <- result %>% pivot_wider(names_from = Dataset, values_from = RMSE)\n",
    "colnames(result_wide)[-1] <- paste0(colnames(result_wide)[-1], \"_RMSE\")\n",
    "\n",
    "ar_values <- c(fmse_ar_monthly, fmse_ar_quarterly, fmse_ar_annual)\n",
    "ar_new_row <- data.frame(Predictor = \"AR(p)\", \n",
    "                         DataMonthly_RMSE = ar_values[1], \n",
    "                         DataQuarterly_RMSE = ar_values[2], \n",
    "                         DataAnnual_RMSE = ar_values[3])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add the new row to the result_wide dataframe\n",
    "result_wide <- rbind(result_wide, ar_new_row)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print the updated result_wide dataframe\n",
    "result_wide\n"
   ]

   "source": [
    "## Ouput Analysis for Single Predictor\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "| Frequency          | Predictor (Min MSFE)          | Predictor Max MSFE           |\n",
    "|--------------------|-------------------------------|-------------------------------|\n",
    "| Monthly            | CrossSectionalPremium (0.0460) | NetEquityExpansion (0.0540) |\n",
    "| Quarterly          | InvestmentCapitalRatio (0.0763) | CorporateBond\\_Return (0.1084) |\n",
    "| Annual             | InvestmentCapitalRatio (0.1617) | TreasuryBill\\_Rate (0.1924) |\n",
    "\n",
    "                                    Table2: Predictors with Min and Max MSFE\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**Minimum MSFE Insights**\n",
    "\n",
    "* The predictor \"CrossSectionalPremium\" has the lowest MSFE of 0.0460 for the Monthly frequency. It suggests that the predictor may more effectively capture short-term market dynamics due to its capacity to reflect current market conditions or diversification benefits within a month.\n",
    "\n",
    "* InvestmentCapitalRatio\" has the lowest MSFE of 0.0763 and 0.1617 at the quarterly and annual frequencies, demonstrating its predictive strength as it may reflect longer-term patterns, potentially explaining their greater predictive ability over lengthy periods. It is likely to capture underlying changes that occur gradually over time.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Maximum MSFE Insights**\n",
    "\n",
    "* The different error rates among predictors and frequencies show that their predicting skills differ. The increased error rate in monthly projections for net equity expansion may imply weak linkage.\n",
    "\n",
    "* The elevated error rate in quarterly forecasts for corporate bond returns may reflect a challenge to catch quarterly fluctuations.\n",
    "\n",
    "* In terms of annual projections, the higher error rate linked with the treasury bill rate may indicate its inability to grasp the complexity of annual market behavior. This emphasizes the significance of aligning predictors with specific periods in order to make a more accurate forecast.\n"
   ]
  },

    "## Comparison with AR modelling\n",
    "* Across various frequencies, the AR(p) model outperforms individual single lagged predictors. This shows that the autoregressive model may capture temporal dependencies in Excess Returns better than individual predictors across these lag intervals.\n",
    "\n",
    "* For reliable forecasts, the AR(p) model emphasises the need of addressing temporal dependence.  However, various predictors perform better at different time frequencies among single lagged predictors, showing their changing significance and alignment with market dynamics over different time periods."
   ]

   "source": [
    "# Function for fitting Linear Model with all predictors\n",
    "'Linear Model using All Predictors'\n",
    "linear_models_all <- function(input){\n",
    "  formula_all_predictors <- paste(\"ExcessReturn ~\", paste(names(input) %>% setdiff(c(\"Time\", \"ExcessReturn\")), collapse=\" + \")) %>% as.formula()\n",
    "  model <- lm(data = input, formula_all_predictors)\n",
    "  summary(model) %>% print()\n",
    "  \n",
    "  RMSE <- mean(model$residuals^2)^0.5\n",
    "  R2 <- summary(model)$r.squared\n",
    "  \n",
    "  \n",
    "  return(list(RMSE = RMSE,R2 = R2))  \n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate Linear Model using all predictors for each dataset\n",
    "M1result <- linear_models_all(input = DataMonthly)\n",
    "Q1result <- linear_models_all(input = DataQuarterly)\n",
    "A1result <- linear_models_all(input = DataAnnual)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Combine results if necessary\n",
    "# final_result <- rbind(results_lm_monthly_all, results_lm_quarterly_all, results_lm_annual_all)\n",
    "lm_all_values <- c(M1result$RMSE, Q1result$RMSE, A1result$RMSE)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a new data frame with the values\n",
    "lm_all_new_row <- data.frame(Predictor = \"LM All Predictors\", \"DataMonthly_RMSE\" = lm_all_values[1], \"DataQuarterly_RMSE\" = lm_all_values[2], \"DataAnnual_RMSE\" = lm_all_values[3])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add the new row to the result_wide dataframe\n",
    "result_wide <- rbind(result_wide, lm_all_new_row)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print the updated result_wide dataframe\n",
    "result_wide"
   ]
  },

    "automatic_model_selection <- function(data, target_column, max_lag = 1) {\n",
    "  data1 <- data\n",
    "  excluded_columns <- c(\"Time\", target_column)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Drop missing values from rows with NaN in ExcessReturn column\n",
    "  data <- data[complete.cases(data$ExcessReturn),]\n",
    "  \n",
    "  predictors <- dplyr::select(data, -excluded_columns)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Extracting the target column\n",
    "  target <- data[[target_column]]\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Lag the predictors\n",
    "  lagged_predictors <- cbind(predictors, dplyr::lag(predictors, 1:max_lag))\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Build the initial formula\n",
    "  formula_1 <- as.formula(paste(\"ExcessReturn ~\", paste(names(lagged_predictors), collapse = \" + \")))\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Use lmSelect for automatic model selection\n",
    "  selected_model <- lm(formula = lmSubsets::lmSelect(formula_1, data = data, penalty = \"BIC\") %>% formula(best = 1), data = data)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Make predictions on lag values\n",
    "  lagged_data <- cbind(data, dplyr::lag(data, 1:max_lag))\n",
    "  lagged_predictions <- predict(selected_model, newdata = lagged_data)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Print selected predictors\n",
    "  cat(\"Selected Predictors:\", attr(terms(selected_model), \"term.labels\"), \"\\n\")\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Print BIC of the selected model\n",
    "  cat(\"BIC:\", BIC(selected_model), \"\\n\")\n",
    "  \n",
    "  rmse = sqrt(mean(selected_model$residuals^2))\n",
    "  cat(\"RMSE:\", rmse, \"\\n\")\n",
    "  \n",
    "  model_summary <- summary(selected_model)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Plot real vs. predicted values\n",
    "  #plot(data1$Time, target, type = \"l\", col = \"grey\", xlab = \"Time\", ylab = \"Excess Return\", main = \"Observed vs. Predicted\")\n",
    "  #lines(data1$Time, lagged_predictions, col = \"blue\", lty = 2)\n",
    "  #legend(\"topright\", legend = c(\"Observed\", \"Predicted (lag values)\"), col = c(\"grey\", \"blue\"), lty = 1:2)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Return the selected model, predictions, RMSE, and model summary\n",
    "  return(list(model = selected_model, predictions = lagged_predictions, rmse = rmse, Msummary = model_summary))\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "M2result <- automatic_model_selection(DataMonthly, \"ExcessReturn\", max_lag = 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "M2result$Msummary\n",
    "\n",
    "Q2result <- automatic_model_selection(DataQuarterly, \"ExcessReturn\", max_lag = 1)\n",
    "Q2result$Msummary\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "A2result <- automatic_model_selection(DataAnnual, \"ExcessReturn\", max_lag = 1)\n",
    "A2result$Msummary\n",
    "\n",
    "best_pred <- c(M2result$rmse, Q2result$rmse, A2result$rmse)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a new data frame with the values\n",
    "best_all_new_row <- data.frame(Predictor = \"Best Mulitple Predictors(BIC)\", \"DataMonthly_RMSE\" = best_pred[1], \"DataQuarterly_RMSE\" = best_pred[2], \"DataAnnual_RMSE\" = best_pred[3])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add the new row to the result_wide dataframe\n",
    "result_wide <- rbind(result_wide, best_all_new_row)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print the updated result_wide dataframe\n",
    "result_wide\n"
   ]

   "source": [
    "# Forward Stepwise \n",
    "### Forward Stepwise Model Selection with Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)\n",
    "\n",
    "Forward stepwise model selection is a method for building predictive models by gradually including predictors that improve the chosen criterion, in this case, the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC).\n",
    "\n",
    "Let Y denote the response variable and X represent the matrix comprising potential predictors.\n",
    "\n",
    "The stepwise algorithm follows the subsequent steps:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Initialization:** An empty model, Y = β0 + ε, is established.\n",
    "    \n",
    "2. **Predictor Assessment:** Simple linear regression models are fitted for each predictor Xi not yet included in the model, utilizing Y as the response and Xi as the predictor.\n",
    "    \n",
    "3. **Criterion Selection:** The BIC is computed for each predictor. The predictor that minimizes the BIC when integrated into the model is chosen.\n",
    "    \n",
    "4. **Model Update:** The chosen predictor, minimizing the BIC, is added to the model: Y = β0 + βjXj + ε.\n",
    "    \n",
    "5. **Iteration:** Steps 2-4 are iterated until either the BIC no longer decreases or a predefined stopping criterion is met.\n",
    "\n",
    "When finished, the final model includes the predictors that minimize the BIC. Their corresponding coefficients (βj) are estimated, indicating the model's best fit according to the BIC criterion.\n"
   ]
  },

    "lag = 0\n",
    "forward_stepwise_forecast <- function(data, target_column) {\n",
    "  data1 <- data\n",
    "  excluded_columns <-  \"Time\"  \n",
    "  # Extracting the target column\n",
    "  target <- data[[target_column]]\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Lagged predictors\n",
    "  predictors <- dplyr::select(data1, -{{target_column}}, -{{excluded_columns}})\n",
    "    # Function to compute BIC\n",
    "  compute_bic <- function(model) {\n",
    "    n <- length(target)\n",
    "    k <- length(coef(model))\n",
    "    resid <- residuals(model)\n",
    "    bic <- n * log(sum(resid^2) / n) + k * log(n)\n",
    "    return(bic)\n",
    "  }\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Initialize an empty model and BIC\n",
    "  selected_predictors <- c()\n",
    "  selected_bic <- Inf\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Perform forward stepwise selection\n",
    "  for (predictor in names(predictors)) {\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Add the predictor to the selected set\n",
    "    selected_predictors <- c(selected_predictors, predictor)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Fit a linear model with the selected predictors\n",
    "    model <- lm(paste(target_column, \"~\", paste(selected_predictors, collapse = \" + \")), data = data1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Compute BIC\n",
    "    bic <- compute_bic(model)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Update the selected predictors if the current model has lower BIC\n",
    "    if (bic < selected_bic) {\n",
    "      selected_bic <- bic\n",
    "    } else {\n",
    "      # If adding the predictor increases BIC, remove it\n",
    "      selected_predictors <- setdiff(selected_predictors, predictor)\n",
    "    }\n",
    "  }\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Final model with selected predictors\n",
    "  final_model <- lm(paste(target_column, \"~\", paste(selected_predictors, collapse = \" + \")), data = data)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Make final predictions\n",
    "  final_predictions <- predict(final_model, newdata = data)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Print selected predictors\n",
    "  cat(\"Selected Predictors:\", selected_predictors, \"\\n\")\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Print BIC of the final model\n",
    "  cat(\"BIC:\", selected_bic, \"\\n\")\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Calculate RMSE\n",
    "  rmse <- sqrt(mean(final_model$residuals^2))\n",
    "  cat(\"RMSE:\", rmse, \"\\n\")\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Plot real vs. predicted values\n",
    "  #plot(data1$Time, target, type = \"l\", col = \"grey\", xlab = \"Time\", ylab = \"Excess Return\", main = \"Observed vs. Predicted\")\n",
    "  #lines(data1$Time, final_predictions, col = \"blue\")\n",
    "  #legend(\"topright\", legend = c(\"Observed\", \"Forecasted\"), col = c(\"grey\", \"blue\"), lty = 1)\n",
    "  \n",
    "  # Return the final model, predictions, selected predictors, BIC, and RMSE\n",
    "  return(list(model = final_model, predictions = final_predictions, selected_predictors = selected_predictors, bic = selected_bic, rmse = rmse))\n",
    "}\n",
    "StepModelM <- forward_stepwise_forecast(DataMonthly, \"ExcessReturn\")\n",
    "StepModelQ <- forward_stepwise_forecast(DataQuarterly, \"ExcessReturn\")\n",
    "StepModelY <- forward_stepwise_forecast(DataAnnual, \"ExcessReturn\")"
   ]

   "source": [
    "# Disparity Among all models\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "* The variation in MSFE across the three distinct modelling methodologies implies varying performance in predicting the Excess Return of the S&P 500 index. When compared to the single lagged predictor linear model and the AR(p) model, the Linear Model with multiple predictors, containing all available variables (LM All Predictors) or selected via BIC criteria (Best Mulitple Predictors(BIC)) and Forward Stepwise selection, has a lower MSFE across all frequencies. \n",
    "\n",
    "* While giving a more comprehensive perspective of market dynamics, the inherent complexity of combining numerous predictors may improve the Linear Model's forecasting accuracy. \n",
    "\n",
    "* In contrast, despite its simplicity, the single lagged predictor model may fail to reflect the intricate relationships inherent in the market, resulting in a comparably larger MSFE. \n",
    "\n",
    "* Furthermore, the AR(p) model performs inconsistently across frequencies, possibly due to intrinsic constraints in capturing the various lag periods, the S&P 500 index data exhibits complicated temporal dependencies. \n",
    "\n",
    "* The differences in predicted accuracy across these models may be due to their different abilities to capture sophisticated market dynamics, temporal interdependence, and the trade-off between simplicity and model comprehensiveness."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Conclusion \n",
    "\n",
    "* Based on the findings of numerous model predictions, it is clear that forecasting stock premiums, specifically Excess Returns of the S\\&P 500 index, is a difficult task. The study used a variety of predictive methodologies, focusing largely on Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) and autoregressive (AR) models to understand and predict stock market behaviour.\n",
    "\n",
    "* In terms of predictive performance, the Linear Model (LM) with all available predictors had the lowest Mean Squared Forecast Error (MSFE) values across annual, monthly, and quarterly frequencies. However, these findings must be approached with caution. While including all predictors resulted in promising accuracy, it may have contributed noise or multicollinearity, so affecting its overall generalizability.\n",
    "\n",
    "* The accuracy of the Single Lagged Predictor models and the AR(p) model, on the other hand, varied among frequencies. The AR(p) model's capacity to capture temporal dependencies outperformed individual predictors, but it displayed inconsistencies across different lag intervals, probably due to the complex temporal interdependencies in the S\\&P 500 index data.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Furthermore, while the Forward Stepwise Model performed well in predictor selection, it did not exceed the Linear Model with all available P predictors, demonstrating a trade-off between model complexity and prediction accuracy.\n",
    "\n",
    "* The variation in MSFE values across models indicates a trade-off between model complexity and accuracy. While comprehensive models that include all predictors appear appealing, their performance should be examined further to ensure that they capture useful information while introducing needless noise. However, the simplicity of single lagged predictors may restrict their ability to grasp the complexities of market dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Finally, the quest for forecasting equity premiums remains complex, emphasising the significance of model selection, predictor relevance, and the dynamic character of market behaviours across several time periods. The findings suggest for a balanced strategy that takes into account both model complexity and predictor inclusivity, while emphasising the importance of identifying predictors that fit more consistently with market dynamics for more accurate forecasts.\n"
   ]
